<a href="#editor-welcome" name="editor-welcome"></a><table width="600" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" class="full-block" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" ><table cellpadding="40" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td align="left" valign="middle" class="text-block" style="padding-bottom:10px; color:#666666; font-size:13px; line-height:22px; " ><div class="mktEditable" id="editor-welcome-title" style="padding-bottom:20px; " ><img style="display: block;" src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/SC2nl-portrait.png" alt="Stephen Casale" align="right"> <span style="color: #666666; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16px;">EDITOR WELCOME</span><br> <span style="margin: 0; font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 24px; text-transform: uppercase;"><span id="docs-internal-guid-0451b2dd-61c9-4db3-68cc-0e388a88e576"><span><span id="docs-internal-guid-de0effd0-58cd-7224-2ed7-ff17905eed17"><span>Code + Friends</span></span></span></span></span><br> <span style="color: #666666; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px;"><a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="https://gopivotal-com.socialcast.com/users/1033819-stephencasale">Steve Casale</a>, Sr. Manager, Corporate Communications</span></div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td align="left" valign="top" class="stack" style="color:#666666; font-size:14px; line-height:22px; padding-bottom:20px; " ><div class="mktEditable" id="editor-welcome-entry" >
<p class="normal">At one dramatic point in <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="http://www.amazon.com/Martian-Andy-Weir/dp/0553418025">The Martian</a>, the abandoned but resourceful botanist Matt Watney uncovers a NASA rover buried in Mars&rsquo; amber sands, and uses the vehicle to subsequently reconnect with his comrades back on Earth.
   Re-establishing bonds with others proved to be as important as his ingenuity (and some intense orbital mechanics) in helping him survive on and eventually leave Mars.
   <br /><br />Software change is a bit like that.
   It requires courage to clear the sands of documentation and protections that accumulate against risk, and rediscover the artifacts of success.
   You need friends too.
   As <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/67833.Extreme_Programming_Explained">Kent Beck</a> famously put it, good software takes good technique <em>and</em> good relationships.
   <br /><br />This issue is peppered with examples of technique and human connection.
   From the East coast we get two miniatures on craft&mdash;the elements of a useful user story from Heddy Stern, and a thoughtful piece on how test-driven design helps one developer transcend ADD (attention deficit disorder).
   Nick Cayou and Josh McKenty give us the state of cloud partnerships&mdash;a terrific and very &ldquo;human build&rdquo; of hard work and influence, while CFO Robert O&rsquo;Donovan connects the dots on a solid quarter in our Business Update.<br /><br />All the pieces of technique and relationships are coming together in our <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" 
href="https://sites.google.com/a/pivotal.io/inside-pivotal/corporate-marketing/events/springone-platform-2016">SpringOne Platform</a> event, and our <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="https://sites.google.com/a/pivotal.io/inside-pivotal/corporate-marketing/events/pivotal-roadshow-2016">Cloud Native roadshows</a>.
   Be sure to ask your developer and customer friends to join us.<br /><br /> Enjoy.</p>
</div>
