<a href="#agile-update" name="agile-update"></a><table width="600" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" class="full-block" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" ><table cellpadding="40" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td align="left" valign="middle" class="text-block" style="padding-bottom:10px; color:#666666; font-size:13px; line-height:22px; " ><div class="mktEditable" id="agile-update-title" style="padding-bottom:20px; " ><img style="display: block;" src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/hstern-portrait.png" alt="Heddy Stern" align="right"> <span style="color: #666666; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16px;">AGILE UPDATE</span><br> <span style="margin: 0; font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 24px; text-transform: uppercase;"><span id="docs-internal-guid-e92b2559-6671-674d-5341-68b630d91b08"><span>The Principles of a Good User Story</span></span></span><br><span style="color: #666666; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px;">Heddy Stern, Product Manager</span></div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td align="left" valign="top" class="stack" style="color:#666666; font-size:14px; line-height:22px; padding-bottom:20px; " ><div class="mktEditable" id="agile-update-entry" >
<p class="normal">Before joining <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="http://pivotal.io/labs">Pivotal Labs</a>, I didn't know what small, incremental, feature-based user stories looked like.
      I was writing 15-page requirement docs or working with developer-written user stories.
      But, since joining <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="https://medium.com/u/8165b1293ea1">Pivotal Labs</a>, I've learned what a really powerful user story can look like for my team.
       And I'd like to share it with you.
      <br /><br /> When I write a story for a Pivotal Labs team, I find that the most successful backlogs are filled with individual user stories that:</p>
<ul>
<li>Are as small as possible;&nbsp;</li>
<li>Clearly matter to the user;&nbsp;</li>
<li>Are independent of other stories; and&nbsp;</li>
<li>Make it clear to everyone when the feature is done.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>
<p class="normal">As an example, I decided to try this exercise with an app I'm really excited about&mdash;Cambridge-based <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="http://www.hopper.com/">Hopper</a>&mdash;an app for booking cheap flights.
      (Note, I've never actually worked on this app.) <br /><br /> How this story would have come to be: Let's assume Mike (our user persona) is searching for a new one-way flight.
      He can already see his search results listed by price of the flight.
      We learned that Mike uses hopper to book vacations but has a limited number of vacation days.
      He wants to make sure that his flight doesn't interfere with their workday schedule and doesn't add extra vacation time to their trip.
      <br /><br />Based on that problem, the product and design team would have come up with the following  feature and user story:<br /><br /> <img src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/agileupdate1v4n5.jpeg" alt="user story" width="500" /><br /><br /><img src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/agileupdate2v4n5.jpeg" alt="visual flow" width="500" /><br /><em><span 
