<a href="#people-update" name="people-update"></a><table width="600" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" class="full-block" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" ><table cellpadding="40" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td align="left" valign="middle" class="text-block" style="padding-bottom:10px; color:#666666; font-size:13px; line-height:22px; " ><div class="mktEditable" id="people-update-title" style="padding-bottom:20px; " ><img style="display: block;" src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/matthewkleinman-nl-portrait.png" alt="Matthew Kleiman" align="right"><span style="color: #666666; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16px;">PEOPLE UPDATE</span><br> <span style="margin: 0; font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 24px; text-transform: uppercase;"><span id="docs-internal-guid-e92b2559-6678-2edb-d7be-ad35822620b9"><span><span id="docs-internal-guid-c78ad48f-38f4-09c9-4adc-dfa4089374d1"><span><span id="docs-internal-guid-dfe2020a-a588-171b-b662-6e03c9e0d265"><span>Distraction: No Longer a Four Letter Word, Thanks to TDD</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><br> <span style="color: #666666; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px;"><span id="docs-internal-guid-dfe2020a-a589-43b4-f600-b70e6448e959"><span>Matthew Kleiman, Software Engineer</span></span><br></span></div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td align="left" valign="top" class="stack" style="color:#666666; font-size:14px; line-height:22px; padding-bottom:20px; " ><div class="mktEditable" id="people-update-entry" >
<p class="normal"><img src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/PEOPLE_TDD driving sign.jpeg" alt="test driving road sign" width="500" height="325" /><br /><br />I've come across various strategies and tools that developers use to deal with ADD and other learning disabilities.
   I've tried many of them during my eight years in the tech industry before I joined Pivotal Labs.
   (You can find more on those in a post I recently <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="https://medium.com/@prismaticorb/distraction-no-longer-a-four-letter-word-thanks-to-tdd-16b9955f0b7#.e8qfrryj4">wrote for Medium</a>.)  <br /><br /> There is also a lot to be said for test-driven development (TDD), a core practice at Pivotal Labs.
   I used to fear distractions as the greatest enemy to my productivity, but TDD allows me to scaffold my code creation process in such a way that distractions don't cause problems.
   In fact, TDD is a natural and powerful method to aid the differently-abled programmer.
   <br /><br /> In TDD, we're fundamentally starting our code writing process from the user's perspective.
   Often we start by writing or modifying a feature test to describe the new behavior that we expect our application to fulfill.
   Of course, the test will fail because the code has yet to be written, but now we have scaffolded the task at hand.
   TDD requires discipline to engage in this step-by-step approach, because it always follows this specific path: Express a desired behavior in the form of a test, watch the test fail, then implement new code until the test passes.
   The algorithm is naturally recursive&mdash;you might start by writing that failing feature test and find yourself writing a failing unit test for an inner module, while the feature test is still failing.
   <br /><br /> As developers continue to use TDD, they find their work continuously scaffolded by the tests they've written.
   It's this continuous scaffolding that allows the programmer with ADD to no longer be afraid of distractions.
   With TDD, I don't have to expend extra energy to fight against the myriad distractions that occur in any software development environment.
   I simply let the distractions in, whether they be a question from a team member or a client who needs support.
   But I have confidence that when I come back to the code, I can just run my tests, see what is failing, and pick up from there, because a failing test will always tell me what to do next.</p>
</div>
